Equation (4) revealed that the frequency of a fragment in the computational simulation study should be no less than 400 to get a % CV (σ/μ*100) within 5%, and no less than around 10 000 to get that within 1%. As a result, 400 and 100 000 are the lowest number of repeated (1 000 000 cleavage) simulations needed for 95% or 99% confidence in the intensity value for all peaks. According to expression 1, the largest i given number of amino acids N and cleavage number n is N‐n, P(b

i
). The expected frequencies of the largest ion can be written as a multiple of total simulation number S and the probability following expression 1. So, for any computational simulation of fragment abundance, to get 5% CV for the distribution, there should be the expected frequencies of the largest fragments as follows:
